content: Please enter your age in years.
name: Age

content: Are there any other languages that you speak or understand? Please describe them briefly here. Example: understand Spanish from high school classes, speak a little Hindi with grandmother
name: AnyOtherLang

content: What language are you most comfortable with using? Who did you learn it from, and starting at what age? (Please be specific, for example, say Mandarin rather than Chinese; American English rather than English.) Example: American English, parents, starting at birth
name: DomLang

content: Please answer these questions for the language you are most comfortable with.
name: DomLangQs

content:
Before we start the main experiment, let's do a quick test. In each trial, you will hear a word “Add” or “At”. Press the corresponding key to indicate whether it is "At" or "Add". If you are not sure, make your best guess.

Let's listen to some examples!
name: EXP9a_DiscriminationI

content:
Excellent! Now please read the instruction carefully for the following task. In each trial, you will hear a series of short tones followed by a word. For this task, only pay attention to the word. Your job is to respond whether the word is “Add” or “At”. Press the corresponding key to indicate which word you heard. If you are not sure, please make the best guess as you can

Let's listen to some examples!
name: EXP9a_MainI

content:
This is the last section of the experiment!!

In each trial, you will hear a word. Press the corresponding key to indicate which word you heard. If you are not sure, make your best guess.
name: EXP9a_PrescreenI

content:
Excellent! Now please read the instruction carefully for the following task. In each trial, you will hear a series of short tones followed by a longer tone. For this task, only pay attention to the last tone. Your job is to respond whether the last tone feels shorter or longer. Press the corresponding key to indicate whether it is SHORTER or LONGER. If you are not sure, please make your best guess.

Let's listen to some examples!
name: EXP9b_MainI

content:
This is the last section of the experiment!!

In each trial, you will hear a tone. Press the corresponding key to indicate whether it is SHORTER or LONGER. If you are not sure, make your best guess.
name: EXP9b_PrescreenI

content: Congradulations! You've completed the main task. We just have a few important questions to ask you before you go...
name: Instruction_Q

content:
Below are my final reminders.

(1) Use your keyboard to respond instead of using your mouse.
(2) DON'T THINK. Follow your first intuition to make response ASAP. You cannot get it correct by thinking.
(3) The total time will depend on your response time, so try to respond as correct and fast as possible.
(4) This task is HARD, and thus requires your undivided attention, so please put away your phone or other distractors whlie doing this experiment.

That's all I have for you. Please try your best! Good luck.
name: Instruction_main

content:
Welcome!


In this study, you will listen to a series of sounds and press keys to enter a response. It will take less than 60 mins to finish this experiment.
Please use earphones, earbuds or headphones while completing the task. Please adjust your volume to a comfortable sound level.
You will begin with a questionnaire asking about your listening devices and how noisy your current environment is.
name: LandingWelcome

content: Please briefly list the language(s) you use in the following situations: at home; in dorm/apartment; while doing math in your head; while thinking; which one you would use for the rest of your life if you could pick just one. Example response: Home: Spanish; Dorm: English; Math: English; Thinking: English; Rest of life: Italian.
name: LangPrefs

content: What language are you NEXT most comfortable with using? Who did you learn it from, and starting at what age? (Please be specific, for example, say Mandarin rather than Chinese; American English rather than English.) Example: Spanish, grandmother, starting at age 5
name: NonDomLang

content: Please answer these questions for the language you are most comfortable with.
name: NonDomLangQs

content: What did you think this experiment was about? Did you notice any recurring patterns?
name: debrief1

content: Did you change how you were answering at any time during the study? What did you change?
name: debrief2

content: The target tone in each series of tones were created from the words such as “Add” and “At”. Did you perceive or “feel” them as being words, or did they just sound like musical tones that have nothing to do with words? Answer “Words” or “Musical Tones” here and you will have a chance to describe more in the next question.
name: debrief3

content: The previous question asked whether you perceive or “feel” the sound as being words, or musical tones. Please explain your answer to that question in more details.
name: debrief4

content:
Good job! Ok, let's move on to the real experiment now.

You won't see or hear the feedback in the following session. It is VERY IMPORTANT that you pay attention to the last sound. Below are my final reminders.

(1) Use your keyboard to respond instead of using your mouse.
(2) DON'T THINK. Follow your first intuition to make response ASAP. You cannot get it correct by thinking.
(3) The total time will depend on your response time, so try to respond as fast as you can while still getting the right answers.
(4) This task is HARD, and thus requires your undivided attention, so please put away your phone or other distractors while doing this experiment.

That's all I have for you. Please try your best! Good luck.
name: finalreminder

content: Please use earphones, earbuds or headphones for this study. Are you using any of them now?
name: logistic_headphone1

content: Which of the following listening devices are you currently using?
name: logistic_headphone2

content: How noisy is your current environment? (1 = Little to no noise, 5 = Very noisy)
name: logistics_noise

content: What instrument(s) do you play (including vocal performance)? How long have you played each one? For examples: Guitar, 6 - 9 years old; Drum, 3 - 20 years old; Vocal, 18 - 20 years old
name: musicbackground1

content: Have you taken any music courseworks? If so, what classes were you taking? How long have you taken them? For example: one quarter of music theory; three quarters of music history; one quarter of music appreciation.
name: musicbackground2

content: Please let us know anything about your musical experiences that you think is important but was not addressed in the previous two questions.
name: musicbackground3
